segments.text: of Mike Coker, C-O-K-E-R, the current planning director for the city of Dallas.
And I'd like to start out, Mike, with asking you a bit about your background and how you came to be in the position you now enjoy.
spent four years in the Army in the late 60s and early 70s.
And upon getting out of the military, moved to Colorado, where I got my undergraduate degree in law enforcement administration and my master's degree in public administration.
I spent about eight years in law enforcement in Colorado.
In 1979, I got my first non-police administrative job as an assistant director of planning in the city of Lakewood, Colorado.
Essentially, my function was over code enforcement and building inspection and plan review.
It included zoning,
interpretation and enforcement as well as all of the environmental ordinances of the city and plan review and building inspection enforcement.
I did that for about a year and a half and moved to the city of Lubbock, Texas where I spent three years as the building official
but also Assistant Director of the Planning Department there, and Jim Bergman, who you may know, who has very, very well brought up the planning in West Texas.
After three years there, the city of Dallas contacted me, and they were having some difficulty with the building inspection division.
At that time, it was a section of planning.
Building inspection was a large division of the planning department.
And you had mentioned Jack Shute.
And Jack was the one who got the building inspection division as part of the planning department.
But he came to the city of Dallas.
because of some internal reorganization back during the Shoup era and just post-Shoup.
and Cree Wilson era.

They decided that they wanted the building inspection function, even though it still is responsible for zoning enforcement, to be placed under the public works department because of the interrelationship and the construction related activities, not the zoning part.
That was ancillary, so they took it over there.
I came to work for the city of Dallas then in January of 84.
and worked in public works for about a year and a half, at which time the city manager here asked me to come to the planning department over the development services side as an assistant director.
Development services here has three major functions, zoning, applications for changes,
subdivision application, zoning board of adjustment, three major activities, as well as the responsibility for all of the city's base maps in both subdivisions and zoning.
And they had some mechanical problems and some timing problems that they needed help with.
So I came down and I did that for about a year.
And then I got a promotion to director of budget and research last year.
And I did that through the last tenuous budget cycle.
And on October 1st, I was promoted then to Director of Planning and Development for the City of Dallas, primarily because

I understand the relationships that exist within this corporate structure of the city of Dallas, and I have a large number of contacts in the public environment that extend beyond our corporate boundaries, that physical city hall environment, and rather than going outside of the

city to look for a director, they felt like I had the background and the ability to help implement some management and some council policies that the city has been actively pursuing for a number of years.

among those policies and processes that the city has been dealing with for the last number of years are the planning policies implementation program which was adopted by the city council in 1984 the implementation of then two new programs that derived from the planning policies and one of those is the growth policy plan if you will with me read comprehensive plan growth policy plan comprehensive plan well it's not as

broad brushed as a comprehensive plan in the technical sense it's going to be as close as the city of Dallas ever has been to a comprehensive plan assuming that the council adopts my assumption is that they will because they said that they wanted at this time the second part of that was to develop a
a new, less cumulative set of zoning districts in order for the public to know what was allowed
within very limited framework on parcels of land in the city of Dallas.
I understand that it's quite a departure from the old ordinance.
Absolutely.

It's completely different and it's broader in that we have a lot of new districts that we didn't have before, but each of the districts is much more narrowly defined than before, and the cumulative zoning districts
And once you got to an HC district, you could have everything that preceded it.
But under this current program, if you have something that is
Let's see, regional retail, which might be the equivalent of the old shopping center or something.
I mean, you know what you can have there, and it's not everything that preceded it.
There are finite limits to what you've got.
But that's just an adjunct to what we're talking about.
Those two things...
are policies and ordinances that the City Council needs to adopt.

As a result of that, we've come into an area that's known as transition, the transition policy that helps us get from the existing zoning ordinance, which has been on the map for 27 years, and the new ordinance, which will take effect ostensibly on July 19, 1989.
And the transition is how we get from here, where we are today, to there in an orderly fashion.
That could be quite awkward.
It's going to be a very unique test of our ability to communicate with the public.
Do you think that there will be many suits involved?
I don't know.
I think a lot of it depends upon how well we do communicate with our constituency.
If you look at it in a broader perspective, most of the residential, especially single-family, duplex, multi-family, they are direct transition.
They go from what they are today to what they
will be next time, and all we're doing is adding an A behind the designation.
I mean, they're exactly the same.
So that takes about 85% of the city, so that leaves 15%.
That 15% is comprised of about 30,000 property owners, and that's all the non-residential property in the city.
But that 30,000 properties, there's probably 18,000 owners.

Of the 18,000 owners, my suspicion is that both of those are not going to have too much to say about it because if they've got construction out there, then it becomes conforming by and large unless it's in a box of shoes or something.
which we've got it down to maybe 5,000 people who may not be happy with what we're proposing.
We'll work with those people on an individual basis to try and help them along, giving them a menu of things to choose from in some cases and recommending other things.
So you'll get down to there's a certain percentage that we're probably going to have to spend a lot of time with, and they may be the ones that sue us.
How long has the ordinance been in preparation?
Well, if you go back, if you use the planning policies as phase one, we worked for about three years on the preparation of the planning policies, but really got into it in the post-shoot era.
Have any neighborhood groups or special interest groups been participating in the reformulation of the organization?
Oh, absolutely.
Absolutely.
The program has been broad-based throughout the city of Dallas.
254 organized neighborhood groups that we interact with on a regular basis, and each of those have strong vocal memberships.
The key player, however, for the residential side has been the Dallas Homeowners League, and they're an umbrella organization that take in 171 of the 254
neighborhood organizations we have a couple of other significant property homeowner property associations that are umbrella in nature and citizens for
for planning, and there's two or three other acronyms that I can't remember.
But they all had an active role in this process.
And the process has been going on, frankly, since 1984 when we adopted the planning policies.
OK. How do you manage this?
How is it structured in terms of achieving good relationship between the planning agency staff and the neighboring groups or the special interest groups?
A couple of years ago, Dennis Wilson, who was the director of the planning department for three years, just preceding me, was authorized to increase his staff by three members.
One of the members is Ray Stanton, who used to be an assistant director of the planning department over the comprehensive planning division.
But he is now an assistant director over the planning policies implementation team.
So the planning policies implementation team, which has this, it's actually four people now, who are the focus of our interactive approach, along with support from each of the other divisions.
I mean, he can take resources that he needs on a temporary basis to support him, like graphics support, comprehensive planning support, special studies.
These people all have other full-time jobs as well as being support to this planning policies implementation team.
But the strategy was to have this planning policies implementation team be the locus of our interactive effort with the community.
I'm not trying to say that it was interacting with DHL or interacting with NAIOP, the National Association of Industrial and Office Parks.
They were very strong players, but they played
with this policy group, planning policies group.
And that's been a very difficult marriage over the last two or three years.
And we've gotten down, since August, we've developed a transition policy since August.

And members from this diverse group of citizens sat on this committee, which was chaired by one of our city council members, and they hammered out this transition policy, which was adopted in January with final refinement.
scheduled for June 30th.
The council?
Yes.
And so, I mean, it's been a multi-phase mechanism, and it hasn't been smooth.
I mean, it's been a painful, painful process.
Jim Reed, if you haven't talked to Jim, you probably need to talk to Jim.
He's the assistant city manager, and he has four departments that have a lot of development-related activities.

But he said as recently as yesterday when we were briefing the plan commission on our Dallas area rapid transit program and our transition program that if anybody ever hires him again to rezone their city, he's going to tell them no because it's a very painful, excruciatingly painful process that
forces you as an individual and a group to muster all of your political skills, your negotiation skills, your ability to field a lot of abuse, and to do it for a continued period of time.
And we had all of that here.
And what we seem to have now is pretty close to a rocky consensus.
Now, the zoning ordinance has been adopted.
The city council adopted the new zoning ordinance last month as well.
And we're refining it, but I mean, it's the law.
And anybody who comes in and applies after Sunday for a zoning change applies for a new zoning district and a new zoning ordinance.
This is part of the transition strategy.
I see.
You mentioned something about 1989.
That's the date that it becomes effective for the entire city.
So as we go through the transition policy and the transition program, we're going to try and get voluntary conversion into this new zoning ordinance.
But if we haven't done that, if we've got people who've held out, if we've got people who have sued us, I mean, whatever reason, we haven't gotten them to agree that this new zoning is proper.
then on that date certain, all the zoning in the city of Dallas changes.
And that's the point in time, I think, if we're going to be sued.
And I have no reason to suspect that we will not
We'll find out.
But I don't expect it, Bob, to be a groundswell of suits.
But I do expect to be suits on it.
And maybe some class action stuff.
I'd be surprised, just in general, if any city in this position went on suit.
I agree.
It's almost to be expected.
But I want to ask you.
It's been a five-year process.
I mean, that's the point.
It's been a five-year process.
And that's what we thought it would take once we adopted the planning policies.

Well, if you work with special interest groups and so forth, you probably have then fostered a great deal of understanding on the part of a great segment of the public that can support what has happened.
Well, that's what I'm concerned about.
I mean, we've dealt directly with a lot of people, but there are a million people in this city.
And not all the people that we've dealt with even live in the city.
I mean, there are property owners in the city.
And my biggest concern is that we haven't done as effective a job of communication with the public as we are going to wish that we had done.
Well, everyone can say that.
Sure.
And let me tell you about our transition program between now and June 30.
Our city has eight council districts.
So the city's broken up into eight council districts.
And they're all elected from their district?
Uh-huh.
Are there any elected at large?
Yes, we have three at large.
Three at large.
And one of those is the mayor.
So we have 11 council members all together.
We have proposed and the council has endorsed that we have two
transition meetings in each council district between April 15th and June 1st.
So that's 16 meetings in six weeks.
But we're really shooting for four weeks because we want some time to
put the information together in a comprehensive form and give it to the city council before they have to vote on any changes.
And they have set a date of June 30th to endorse wholly the transition program.
We've done it in concept and never even say yea or nay on the 30th of June.
What we intend to do is we are going to notify every property owner in the city of Dallas
of the transition meetings.
And we're also going to try and tell the property owner, if it's a direct transition, i.e., MF1 to MF1A, what that means to them.
What's the consequence?
That's right.
There's no change.
There's change in the letter.
You can still do what you've been doing.
You can have the same number of units, the same heights, that kind of stuff.
And then for those 30,000...
This will have to be by mail?
Yeah.
In fact, we're going to vend it out.
But we're going to validate the mailing so that we can...
The mailing list and the validation process is our deal, because it's state law so-so.
But we're going to have a vendor do it, and we figure it's going to cost us $200,000.
At least it won't take staff time away.
There might be more staff time.
The city council on Wednesday said that we can have $350,000 to do that this year.
We can't hire any staff, but there are staff that we'll hire, but they won't belong to us.
They'll be consultant or vendor people.
They won't be regular civil service.
Which is fine with me because I don't want to expand my staff.
I'd like to expand my staff, but not for this process because this is a temporary thing.
It's busy work.
That's right.
And so we're going to bend that out.
Then, remembering that the new ordinance
was adopted and effective March 1st, which is Sunday, any application for zoning, for rezoning in the city of Dallas will be against that standard.
That's the first phase.
The transition thing, anybody that volunteers to transition into the new zoning district, that'll be done in a subpoenaing change.
And we think that we're probably going to handle 90% of the city that way.
Let me ask you this question.
How do you feel about zoning in general?
What is the basis for your zoning?
Let me ask you that first.
You need to be clear on the question.
I'm not sure I understand.
What is the value basis for your zoning ordinance?
On what foundation does your zoning rest?
Health, safety, and welfare.
It's not a common basis.
How do you make, how are those determinations made?
What I'm trying to get at is...
Compatibility.
I mean, we're talking about compatibility abuses.
I don't know if I'm getting where you want to go.
Well, I probably should ask a more direct question.
You don't have an adopt-accompanism plan.
No.
To base it on.
And under the state-enabling legislation, they mentioned something about this.
Sure they did.
How do you feel about that?
I think I need to answer your question a couple of ways.
One way is that our city attorney, since 1965, has interpreted our zoning map, which is comprised of 155 1-400 scale maps, as the plan for the city of Dallas.
Wrong.
I'm just telling you what our understanding is.
Your previous attorney would not have done that.
Irrespective.
Irrespective.
But to answer the question about a comprehensive plan for the city of Dallas, I think that it would have been a useful tool
for a long, long time to help us in the growth management of our city.
Not to control it, I'm not talking about control, I'm talking about management.
And as we get closer to a growth policy plan that encompasses the best parts of comprehensive planning,
My thought is that it will become the tool for the next two decades because it's a living document.
If you just make a plan that dies, then it's no good.
But if you have a plan that is a living document and it changes with the tide of our city, because cities are not static.
Any city that is static is in serious trouble.
The values change.
Exactly, exactly.
And I'm talking both political values and cultural values are tied together.
traditional values.
One of the things that's happening in Texas, and I suspect that you're really close to it, is that Texas is not the Texas that you knew 20 years ago.
I'm married to a Texan.
I have been for 20 years from Waco.
And she tells me that Texas isn't Texas anymore.
I said, what do you mean that Texas isn't Texas anymore?
Well, Texas isn't for Texans.
Be specific.
Well, there's too many people from the Northwest.
There's too many people from the Northeast.
There's too many people from the Midwest.
There's too many people from Florida and San Diego.
I'm from San Diego.
And I said, well, what difference does that make?
And she says, well, they've brought all these different cultures, these values, these perceptions, and that's
impacting, having a direct impact on Texas.
Well, I still think that Texas is Texas.
I just think Texas is getting better because when you have the diverse opportunities that are presented from different perspectives,
you get a better environment to live in.
But let me go back to...
It's something that's enriching.
Absolutely.
The melting pot...
I don't want to talk about illegal aliens or anything else because that's somebody else's deal.
But I think that diverse cultures, diverse points of view help a city like the city of Dallas to become... We've talked about international.
It allows us to become more of a...
competitor in the international scheme of things and in the national scheme of things and on top of that in the state scheme of things.

For example, I have a friend from Stockholm who visited Dallas specifically to see this building and the library and a few other buildings in town as outstanding examples of international scale architecture.
And I think that Dallas has made a conscious effort in that direction.
And we are continuing to do that, Bob.

But to talk about the comprehensive planning perspective just a little bit longer, I think that the time has really come for us to have a document that we can use as the framework for the development of our city and the redevelopment.
I mean, we've got to talk about both pieces of this puzzle.

For two decades now, if you assume that the zoning ordinance that we've adopted that becomes effective for the entire city in July of 1989 will be the document subject to some changes that we're going to use for the next 20 years, because that's the last one lasted since 1965.
That's 22 years.
then we've got to have a plan to reinforce our zoning.
And I don't think that you can have a quality...
The question isn't the tail wagging the dog.
Today is.
But once we have a plan, then I think that the dog will once again be in the leadership position.
Then the plan may have something in it that suggests that the ordinance would have to be modified.
It will.
See, one of the things that we are doing with the zoning ordinance that they just adopted is they also said that we know
that there's going to be refinements to this.
We know that there are going to be changes to this document and that's what the transition program should help us accomplish because they've given two and a half years to the transition.
I mean it wasn't today it all changed and part this is a conscious decision on the part of the council to help us refine that ordinance so that when we get to 1989 we've got the document
the written document, I mean the growth policy plan, and it's supported by the zoning ordinance.
Then they play together, and those two pieces of this puzzle together then become, in my interpretation, the comprehensive plan for the city of Dallas.
And the tail and dog scenario is really true.

If you make the assumption that the zoning that was placed on the map in 1965 was all correct, which I would venture to say was not correct, but if you made the assumption that it was correct, then why have we allowed so many changes in the zoning over the course of the 22 years?
And I'm not saying that we're not going to have changes in zoning then either, because we're rezoning 276,000 pieces of property in the city of Dallas with this transition process.
And when the smoke clears, there's going to be people out there that are not, even if they agree today, that they'll accept CS zoning instead of SC zoning.
Five years hence, they may think that that needs to be a higher density.
